value.value: The region of the cytoplasm located at the apical side of the cell. Used in reference to animal polarized epithelial cells.
The region of the cytoplasm located at the basolateral side of the cell. Used in reference to animal polarized epithelial cells.
Tubulo-vesicular structure located in the apical cytoplasm that participates in apical cargo recycling in polarized epithelial cells.
Tubulo-vesicular structure located in the basolateral cytoplasm that participates in basolateral cargo recycling in polarized epithelial cells.
Binding to a junction formed at the point where double-stranded telomeric DNA becomes a single-stranded G-rich telomeric DNA 3' overhang.

A telomere maintenance process that results in the formation of a telomeric circle, or t-circle. A t-circle is an extrachromosomal duplex or single-stranded circular DNA molecule composed of t-arrays. T-circles are involved in the control of telomere length via alternative-lengthening of telomeres (ALT) pathway and telomere rapid deletion (TRD).
The telomere maintenance process in which telomeric loops are disassembled to permit efficient telomere replication.
A biochemically and structurally distinct domain of the retinal interphotoreceptor matrix that is specifically associated with cone photoreceptor cell inner and outer segments.
The behavior of an organism relating to the progression of that organism along the ground by the process of lifting and setting down each leg.

The neurological system process driven by motile cilia on ependymal cells of the brain by which cerebrospinal fluid circulates from the sites of secretion to the sites of absorption. In ventricular cavities, the flow is unidirectional and rostrocaudal, in subarachnoid spaces, the flow is multi-directional.

A box H/ACA ribonucleoprotein complex that contains the RNA component of vertebrate telomerase, the enzyme essential for the replication of chromosome termini in most eukaryotes. This ribonucleoprotein complex is a structural box H/ACA RNP, which does not have the catalytic pseudouridylation function shared by the majority of H/ACA RNPs present in the cell.
The series of molecular signals generated as a consequence of the peptide neurotransmitter galanin binding to a cell surface receptor.

Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or a multicellular organism (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a higher than normal number of multicellular organisms living per unit area.
A protein complex containing at least one glycosylated protein, may be held together by both covalent and noncovalent bonds.

definition.value: An example is the Dictyostelium multi protein pspB complex, which is secreted from prespore vesicles and incorporated into the spore coat.

value.value: A process in which a small Cajal body-specific RNA is transported to, or maintained in, a Cajal body.

label.value: cell chemotaxis to vascular endothelial growth factor

value.value: The directed movement of a motile cell in response to the presence of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF).

label.value: endothelial cell chemotaxis to vascular endothelial growth factor

value.value: The directed movement of an endothelial cell in response to the presence of vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF).
Prevention of degradation of telomerase RNA (TERC) molecules.
A process in which an RNA is transported to, or maintained in, a Cajal body.

label.value: telomerase RNA localization to Cajal body

value.value: A process in which telomerase RNA (TERC) is transported to, or maintained in, a Cajal body.
Any process in which telomerase RNA is transported to, or maintained in, a specific location.
The binding of an endothelial cell to the extracellular matrix via adhesion molecules.
The binding of an endothelial cell to the extracellular matrix via fibronectin.
The cell-cell adhesion process by which adjacent microvilli attach to each other through Ca(2+)-dependent adhesion links made of protocadherin-24 and mucin-like protocadherin.

label.value: calcium ion transmembrane transport via low voltage-gated calcium channel

value.value: A process in which a calcium ion is transported from one side of a membrane to the other by means of a low voltage-gated calcium channel.
A phenotypic switching process where a cell reversibly differentiates and dedifferentiates from one cell type into another.

label.value: cell dedifferentiation involved in phenotypic switching

value.value: A cell dedifferentiation process that is a part of a reversible switch of a cell from one cell type or form to another, at a frequency above the expected frequency for somatic mutations.

label.value: cell differentiation involved in phenotypic switching

value.value: A cell differentiation process that is a part of a reversible switch of a cell from one cell type or form to another, at a frequency above the expected frequency for somatic mutations.

label.value: viral release via disruption of host outer membrane

value.value: The dissemination of mature viral particles from a host cell via the destabilization of the cell outer membrane.
A G protein-coupled receptor activity that is responsible for the sense of taste.
A G protein-coupled receptor activity that is responsible for the sense of bitter taste.
A G protein-coupled receptor activity that is responsible for the sense of sweet taste.
A non-GPCR transmembrane signaling receptor activity that is responsible for contact chemoreception.
A macromolecular localization process in which RNA is transported to and maintained in a location within the nucleus.

label.value: glycine betaine-activated nonselective monoatomic cation channel activity

value.value: Enables the transmembrane transfer of a monoatomic cation by a channel that opens when glycine betaine has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.

label.value: activation of meiosis I spindle assembly checkpoint

value.value: Any process that starts the inactive process of a meiosis I cell cycle spindle assembly checkpoint.
The part of the cleavage furrow closest to the cell surface.
The 'trough' of the cleavage furrow. This is the part of the cleavage furrow closest to the contractile ring.

The regionalization process that specifies plant organ primordium boundaries resulting in a restriction of organogenesis to a limited spatial domain and keeping the organ separate from surrounding tissues.
The site on the mitochondrial membrane where the separation of a single continuous mitochondrial membrane into two membranes occurs as a final step in mitochondrial fission.

A plant organ developmental process during which a plant dismantles cellular components to reclaim the cellular building blocks and nutrients that have been deposited in the plant organs during growth.
A eukaryotically conserved heterodimeric protein complex (comprising adherin and the chromatid cohesion factor MAU2/Scc4/Ssl3) required for the loading of a cohesin, complex onto DNA.

A eukaryotically conserved heterodimeric protein complex (comprising Wings apart-like protein and the Pds5 Armadillo repeat cohesin associated protein) involved in the loading and unloading of a cohesin complex onto DNA.

Development, taking place during the post-embryonic phase of a plant tissue or tissues that work together to perform a specific function or functions. Development pertains to the process whose specific outcome is the progression of a structure over time, from its formation to the mature structure. Organs are commonly observed as visibly distinct structures, but may also exist as loosely associated clusters of cells that work together to perform a specific function or functions.

Morphogenesis, during the post-embryonic phase, of a plant tissue or tissues that work together to perform a specific function or functions. Morphogenesis pertains to process in which anatomical structures are generated and organized. Organs are commonly observed as visibly distinct structures, but may also exist as loosely associated clusters of cells that work together to perform a specific function or functions.
The process, occurring after plant embryonic development, by which anatomical structures are generated and organized.
The process in which the identity of a plant organ is maintained. Identity is considered to be the aggregate of characteristics by which a structure is recognized.
The regionalization process in which the identity of a plant organ primordium is specified. Identity is considered to be the aggregate of characteristics by which a structure is recognized.
Catalysis of the reaction: nicotinate + UDP-D-glucose = O-D-glucosylnicotinate + UDP.
A plant cell papilla that is part of a trichome cell.
